><hr size=1> Vaal looked at the simple marker, his eyes bright with unshed tears. He thought about the loss of the halfling he called his mentor, Gibbs Grumblebelly.Gibbs left the way he wanted to, relaxing in the shade of the oak tree in Rivervale, with no worries of where the dragon was or why everything in fear was attacking him.<br>
<br>
Vaal thought about the time he met Gibbs in the entrance to Crushbone, how amazed he was at the power wielded by the warrior, and how he let him try on the bronze breastplate, or when they met in Lesser Faydark, even more memories came back in a rush, Vaal staggered with the loss.<br>
<br>
He looked up at his wife, crying as she held onto him for support. He looked at all Gibbs' friends gathered around the small coffin and looked up into the bright sun wondering why Gibbs had to go. &quot;Gibbs would have loved a day like today, to be relaxing on his hammock and drinking an ale&quot;, the thought broke Vaal completely, he sobbed unashamedly.<br>
<br>
As the coffin was lowered into the grave, Vaal looked away, praying to Tunare that she would protect and care for one that was so short on stature but so full of heart.<br>
<br>
Long after the others left and into the deepening night, Vaal stood at attention, saluting the halfling he called friend.<br>
<br>
